name: ANNE PRYOR, MA
title: LinkedIn Expert, Sales Trainer, Speaker, Lovitude® Soul Painter 🟣 Create Meaningful Work & Life 🟣 Build Purposeful LinkedIn Presence & Strategies to Look Great, Be Found & Get Known & Make Meaningful Connnections
summary:
Internationally recognized LinkedIn Authority, Sales LinkedIn Trainer, Speaker, Lovitude Soul Painter & Personal Development Coach - I advise, guide, and inspire my brilliant clients to bring their soul to work. I help them Look Great, Be Found, Get Known, Make Connections to find meaningful work, generate sales & hire top talent.

🟣 SUCCESSFUL CLIENTS HIRE ME FOR RESULTS
"I generated over $550,000 after Anne rebuilt my profile and strategy."​ G. Curphy, Awarding-winning Leadership Author
After training global VP SALES and 120 sales reps., the team secured NEW ORDERS.
SMALL BUSINESS OWNER generated IMMEDIATE SALES after I created LinkedIn Profile.
MANUFACTURING company sales leader found 3 connections for immediate new business.
ATTORNEY found new clients after I built her LinkedIn profile and focused branding.
HR RECRUITER hits increased 1225% in 5 hours after working with Anne on recruiting strategy.

🟣 SALES LEADERS ACHIEVE THEIR GOALS
I have trained hundreds of sales teams, business owners, and recruiters to achieve results, facilitating powerful Sales Navigator training that leads to profitable business opportunities.

🟣 RESULTS-FOCUSED LINKEDIN TRAINER FOR 200,000+
"Anne's impactful coaching changed my life. Her strategies and training got me 5 recruiter calls and I landed."

🟣 EXPERT LINKEDIN SERVICES
Write compelling Branded and Search Engine Optimized Profiles LinkedIn profiles, creating differentiation, credibility, and visibility online.
• LinkedIn Sales & Recruitment Training
• Thought Leadership Strategy
•  LinkedIn Company Pages

🟣 INSPIRING KEYNOTE SPEAKER
I speak on topics from LinkedIn for Job Search and Sales, Connecting with Spirit to Access Messages for Creativity, Healing, and Transformation at The Shift Network, IANDS, NABJ, AKA, Children’s Hospital Assn., TeamWomen, MSPBJ, Cargill, Mayo Clinic, WLiT, WIN, and events.

🟣 COACH CLIENTS TO UNEARTH THEIR SOUL'S WORK
I coach my clients to discover who they are, why they are here, what they desire, a d clearly communicate their message to be found.

🟣 LOVITUDE® SOUL PAINTER
My paintings are hanging in Mayo Clinic & galleries, are licensed on products sold globally, proceeds donated to charities. I was a guest on the Hallmark Channel sharing Lovitude & after-death communications

🟣 MY PURPOSE
My Grandma was known as the town matchmaker, my Dad was like “George Bailey", my generous Mom, co-founder of a food shelf, taught us to be kind and give back. I believe what happens to you happens to me; we are here to do good & we need each other.

#LinkedInROCKSTARS

member_experience_collection.title: LinkedIn Sales Trainer | LinkedIn Business Development, LinkedIn Coach, Personal Digital Coach
member_experience_collection.description:
► "Anne, you are awesome! I've never been so grateful to receive an invoice for sales training. I'm thrilled about our relationship and friendship." Steve Blexrud ◄

Provide one on one coaching, group session training and speaking on Career Clarity, Employee and Personal Branding, LinkedIn sales training, and creating online visibility for job transition and business development.

LINKEDIN SALES & LEAD GENERATION TRAINING
♦ Deliver workshops, training sessions, webinars and one on one coaching for sales executives, sales teams, business owners and executives on how to generate leads and create new business opportunities leveraging the power of LinkedIn.

BUILDING COMPANY PAGES / SHOWCASE PAGES
♦ Small Business, Hotels, Non Profit and Organization needing a Company Page.

MARKETING BLOGGING ON LINKEDIN
♦ Create a successful marketing plan and execute a campaign leveraging tips, LinkedIn Long Form Publishing tool, Groups, Home Page and more.

EMPLOYEE BRANDING
♦ Provide employment, employer and employee branding strategies and show employers how to bring them to life online for talent acquisition, business development and branding.

BRANDING ONLINE | LINKEDIN PROFILES + STRATEGIES
♦ Branded LinkedIn profiles and training for HR and sales teams, small business owners, lawyers, attorneys, sales executives, coaches, professional speakers, authors and executives in career transition to be found and to find new business opportunities.

TEACHING, TRAINING, SPEAKING
♦ Teach and speak on Personal Branding, Networking Etiquette, Creating + Communicating Branded LinkedIn Profiles.

HAPPY CLIENTS
♦ Hotels, Manufacturing, Law Firms, Advertising Agencies, Marketing Services Firms, Medical Devices, Financial, VC, PE, Sales, CVB, Call Center, Entertainment, Staffing and Recruiting, Telecommunications.

member_experience_collection.title: Future Mapper, Future Mapping | Whole Brain Charting
member_experience_collection.company_name: Meaningful Connections Retreats at The Collaborative Leadership Center
member_experience_collection.description:
Anne is certified in Future Mapping, Whole Brain Charting, a brand new, altruistic way to create and uncover your desired future, plan and manifest your goals and your soul's desires.

Future Mapping is a proven process used with hundreds of individuals, businesses, associations and government organizations over the past three years in Japan.

Meaningful Connections Consultants Anne Pryor and Risё Kasmirski have been the first in the world, outside of Japan, to be trained on this new technique by Masanori Kanda, #1 Marketer in Japan and developer of this new concept, and Dr. Paul Scheele, of Learning Strategies.

member_experience_collection.description:
Lovitude® means Love and Gratitude.

My intentions is that my jewelry and Lovitude soul paintings emit my quantum energy of love and gratitude.

"L" for Love and "G" for Gratitude are united as a connected symbol of the universe's most powerful positive thought energies. The sphere represents our spirit.

Dr. EMOTO's HIDDEN MESSAGE IN WATER
♦ My awareness of the importance of Love and Gratitude was inspired after watching "What the Bleep Do We Know!?®". Masaru Emoto and his book “The Hidden Messages in Water” uncovered "we must pay respect to water, and feel love and gratitude, and receive vibrations with a positive attitude.

DR. EMOTO'S WATER EXPERIMENTS
♦ In Dr. Emoto's important studies he secured water samples from around the world. He placed the samples in bottles and subjected the water samples to positive words, visuals and music. When these samples were frozen and then thawed, Dr. Emoto's scientist took photos and these samples and the photos showed beautiful hexagonal images. He also subjected bottles of water from the same sources to negative words, visuals and music. These samples were also frozen and as they thawed photos were also taken of these images and these images were ugly, dark, unsightly blobs.

ANNE'S RICE EXPERIMENT
♦ I was encouraged to conduct my own test, with cooked rice which proved “proof positive” and was the inspiration for Lovitude. The experiment started on April 15, 2005 through May 15, 2005. I took four cups of cooked rice and put two cups in one plastic covered container where I wrote Love, Thank You, Lovitude® and the symbol on the container.

EXPERIMENT RESULTS
♦ I took the other two cups of cooked rice and put them into another plastic container.
For 30 days I greeted the rice with the positive words and energy each day. I "dissed", the other rice. See the photo below.

SOUL PAINTINGS ARE VISUAL BLESSINGS
♦ Her Lovitude Soul Paintings have been called ‘visual blessings’, her unusual technique is created with magic alcohol ink, her breath (no paint brushes), and essential oils including Frankincense, myrrh, and other oils that bless each painting. ♦ She was inspired to paint in 2017 after receiving messages from a former colleague, Irene Rossman, who died within three weeks, after being diagnosed with cancer. She continues to receive “After Death Messages” and inspiration.

SOUL PAINTINGS ARE VISUAL BLESSINGS

♦ She was inspired to paint in 2017 after receiving messages from a former colleague, Irene Rossman, who died within three weeks, after being diagnosed with cancer. She continues to receive “After Death Messages” (ACD) and inspiration.

member_projects_collection.name: Meaningful Connections LinkedIn Networking Parties
member_projects_collection.description:
Here's how a Meaningful Connections LinkedIn Party works:

Invite: 3 to 5 people who have different but complimentary networks to a 'LinkedIn Party'.
Meet up: at a location with internet access for instance a coffee shop community room, local community center, library room, virtual office location, the outplacement companies meeting room. In Minneapolis / St. some of our grocery stores have free community rooms .
Bring: computers
Check settings: everyone has their connections open (check the Settings to open connections to Everyone).
Prepare: a list of 10 people that they'd like to meet: titles, industries, companies, specialties, location, size of company, (their target audience).
Take turns: each person gets 10 minutes to ask the other members to search for his / her targeted people.
Search: friends all go to the "Advanced" area located next to the white Search box at the top of the profile page and type in the targeted keywords, titles, industries, companies, locations, etc. and click search.
Make meaningful connection: when the member finds a good connection they send a message, inside of LinkedIn, they include the friend and create a message such as:
"Hi Nate,

I would like to introduce you to my friend Max. He's on my softball team and he is a seasoned product manager who is interested in your advice and expertise around medical device manufacturing as he is seeking to transition from Company X. I am including him on this message and will invite him to reach out to you.

Please let me know what I can be on the look-out for you. I know that when good people meet good things happen.

Be well, my thoughtful friend,
Anne

Nate Nelson: nate.nelson@me.com
Max Smith: maxsmith2@gmail.com"

TIP: I always include the email addresses for each person in the introduction email.

member_projects_collection.name: KEYNOTE SPEAKER | PSA | How Artificial Intelligence and LinkedIn Can Drive Business Success
member_projects_collection.description:
Do you know what your online brand says about you?

Executives and Sales people with an understanding of their own digital visibility are more likely to add credibility and value to their organizations. Are you digitally dressed for success? Is your SEO working? Are you speaker the language of your customers? How does your personal brand and LinkedIn profile help or hurt your business prospects?

78% of sales people that use social media outperform their peers that don’t.
75% of B2B buyers use social media to research their vendors.
74% B2B buyers conduct 50% of their research online before the talk to a sales person.
74% of buyers choose to work with businesses where the sales representative was the first to add value and insight on social media.

Here’s how Anne will show you how to Look Great, Be Found, Get Known and make Meaningful Connections on LinkedIn:

How to Look Great on LinkedIn to Be Found – 5 tips to make sure you come up in keyword searches by clients.
What is Artificial Intelligence and Why You Should Care – how to target a prospect and speak their language to connect meaningfully.
What You Should Really Say on LinkedIn – don’t confuse your brand, what are the 3 themes you want to be known for?

Anne Pryor is known around the world for her expertise in social and online marketing, connection strategy and being found on tools like LinkedIn. She is recognized as the the Top 10 LinkedIn Trainer by Education UK, where she has personally written over 7,400 branded LinkedIn profiles and trained over 80,000 people for successful outcomes.

Anne provides training to groups and organizations and is a coach to individuals, small business owners, entrepreneurs, start up organizations and sales teams in leveraging LinkedIn, social connection and other online tools strategically.

member_projects_collection.name: Meaningful Connections LinkedIn Networking Parties
member_projects_collection.description: Here's how a Meaningful Connections LinkedIn Party works: Invite: 3 to 5 people who have different but complimentary networks to a 'LinkedIn Party'. Meet up: at a location with internet access for instance a coffee shop community room, local community center, library room, virtual office location, the outplacement companies meeting room. In Minneapolis / St. some of our grocery stores have free community rooms . Bring: computers Check settings: everyone has their connections open (check the Settings to open connections to Everyone). Prepare: a list of 10 people that they'd like to meet: titles, industries, companies, specialties, location, size of company, (their target audience). Take turns: each person gets 10 minutes to ask the other members to search for his / her targeted people. Search: friends all go to the "Advanced" area located next to the white Search box at the top of the profile page and type in the targeted keywords, titles, industries, companies, locations, etc. and click search. Make meaningful connection: when the member finds a good connection they send a message, inside of LinkedIn, they include the friend and create a message such as: "Hi Nate, I would like to introduce you to my friend Max. He's on my softball team and he is a seasoned product manager who is interested in your advice and expertise around medical device manufacturing as he is seeking to transition from Company X. I am including him on this message and will invite him to reach out to you. Please let me know what I can be on the look-out for you. I know that when good people meet good things happen. Be well, my thoughtful friend, Anne Nate Nelson: nate.nelson@me.com Max Smith: maxsmith2@gmail.com" TIP: I always include the email addresses for each person in the introduction email.

member_projects_collection.name: Meaningful Connections LinkedIn Networking Parties
member_projects_collection.description:
Here's how a Meaningful Connections LinkedIn Party works:

Invite: 3 to 5 people who have different but complimentary networks to a 'LinkedIn Party'.
Meet up: at a location with internet access for instance a coffee shop community room, local community center, library room, virtual office location, the outplacement companies meeting room. In Minneapolis / St. some of our grocery stores have free community rooms .
Bring: computers
Check settings: everyone has their connections open (check the Settings to open connections to Everyone).
Prepare: a list of 10 people that they'd like to meet: titles, industries, companies, specialties, location, size of company, (their target audience).
Take turns: each person gets 10 minutes to ask the other members to search for his / her targeted people.
Search: friends all go to the "Advanced" area located next to the white Search box at the top of the profile page and type in the targeted keywords, titles, industries, companies, locations, etc. and click search.
Make meaningful connection: when the member finds a good connection they send a message, inside of LinkedIn, they include the friend and create a message such as:
"Hi Nate,

I would like to introduce you to my friend Max. He's on my softball team and he is a seasoned product manager who is interested in your advice and expertise around medical device manufacturing as he is seeking to transition from Company X. I am including him on this message and will invite him to reach out to you.

Please let me know what I can be on the look-out for you. I know that when good people meet good things happen.

Be well, my thoughtful friend,
Anne

Nate Nelson: nate.nelson@me.com
Max Smith: maxsmith2@gmail.com"

TIP: I always include the email addresses for each person in the introduction email.

member_projects_collection.description:
Do you know what your online brand says about you?

Executives and Sales people with an understanding of their own digital visibility are more likely to add credibility and value to their organizations. Are you digitally dressed for success? Is your SEO working? Are you speaker the language of your customers? How does your personal brand and LinkedIn profile help or hurt your business prospects?

78% of sales people that use social media outperform their peers that don’t.
75% of B2B buyers use social media to research their vendors.
74% B2B buyers conduct 50% of their research online before the talk to a sales person.
74% of buyers choose to work with businesses where the sales representative was the first to add value and insight on social media.

Here’s how Anne will show you how to Look Great, Be Found, Get Known and make Meaningful Connections on LinkedIn:

How to Look Great on LinkedIn to Be Found – 5 tips to make sure you come up in keyword searches by clients.
What is Artificial Intelligence and Why You Should Care – how to target a prospect and speak their language to connect meaningfully.
What You Should Really Say on LinkedIn – don’t confuse your brand, what are the 3 themes you want to be known for?

Anne Pryor is known around the world for her expertise in social and online marketing, connection strategy and being found on tools like LinkedIn. She is recognized as the the Top 10 LinkedIn Trainer by Education UK, where she has personally written over 7,400 branded LinkedIn profiles and trained over 80,000 people for successful outcomes.

Anne provides training to groups and organizations and is a coach to individuals, small business owners, entrepreneurs, start up organizations and sales teams in leveraging LinkedIn, social connection and other online tools strategically.

member_projects_collection.description:
Do you know what your online brand says about you?

Executives and Sales people with an understanding of their own digital visibility are more likely to add credibility and value to their organizations. Are you digitally dressed for success? Is your SEO working? Are you speaker the language of your customers? How does your personal brand and LinkedIn profile help or hurt your business prospects?

78% of sales people that use social media outperform their peers that don’t.
75% of B2B buyers use social media to research their vendors.
74% B2B buyers conduct 50% of their research online before the talk to a sales person.
74% of buyers choose to work with businesses where the sales representative was the first to add value and insight on social media.

Here’s how Anne will show you how to Look Great, Be Found, Get Known and make Meaningful Connections on LinkedIn:

How to Look Great on LinkedIn to Be Found – 5 tips to make sure you come up in keyword searches by clients.
What is Artificial Intelligence and Why You Should Care – how to target a prospect and speak their language to connect meaningfully.
What You Should Really Say on LinkedIn – don’t confuse your brand, what are the 3 themes you want to be known for?

Anne Pryor is known around the world for her expertise in social and online marketing, connection strategy and being found on tools like LinkedIn. She is recognized as the the Top 10 LinkedIn Trainer by Education UK, where she has personally written over 7,400 branded LinkedIn profiles and trained over 80,000 people for successful outcomes.

Anne provides training to groups and organizations and is a coach to individuals, small business owners, entrepreneurs, start up organizations and sales teams in leveraging LinkedIn, social connection and other online tools strategically.

member_projects_collection.name: Meaningful Connections LinkedIn Networking Parties
member_projects_collection.description:
Here's how a Meaningful Connections LinkedIn Party works:

Invite: 3 to 5 people who have different but complimentary networks to a 'LinkedIn Party'.
Meet up: at a location with internet access for instance a coffee shop community room, local community center, library room, virtual office location, the outplacement companies meeting room. In Minneapolis / St. some of our grocery stores have free community rooms .
Bring: computers
Check settings: everyone has their connections open (check the Settings to open connections to Everyone).
Prepare: a list of 10 people that they'd like to meet: titles, industries, companies, specialties, location, size of company, (their target audience).
Take turns: each person gets 10 minutes to ask the other members to search for his / her targeted people.
Search: friends all go to the "Advanced" area located next to the white Search box at the top of the profile page and type in the targeted keywords, titles, industries, companies, locations, etc. and click search.
Make meaningful connection: when the member finds a good connection they send a message, inside of LinkedIn, they include the friend and create a message such as:
"Hi Nate,

I would like to introduce you to my friend Max. He's on my softball team and he is a seasoned product manager who is interested in your advice and expertise around medical device manufacturing as he is seeking to transition from Company X. I am including him on this message and will invite him to reach out to you.

Please let me know what I can be on the look-out for you. I know that when good people meet good things happen.

Be well, my thoughtful friend,
Anne

Nate Nelson: nate.nelson@me.com
Max Smith: maxsmith2@gmail.com"

TIP: I always include the email addresses for each person in the introduction email.

member_projects_collection.name: Meaningful Connections LinkedIn Networking Parties
member_projects_collection.description:
Here's how a Meaningful Connections LinkedIn Party works:

Invite: 3 to 5 people who have different but complimentary networks to a 'LinkedIn Party'.
Meet up: at a location with internet access for instance a coffee shop community room, local community center, library room, virtual office location, the outplacement companies meeting room. In Minneapolis / St. some of our grocery stores have free community rooms .
Bring: computers
Check settings: everyone has their connections open (check the Settings to open connections to Everyone).
Prepare: a list of 10 people that they'd like to meet: titles, industries, companies, specialties, location, size of company, (their target audience).
Take turns: each person gets 10 minutes to ask the other members to search for his / her targeted people.
Search: friends all go to the "Advanced" area located next to the white Search box at the top of the profile page and type in the targeted keywords, titles, industries, companies, locations, etc. and click search.
Make meaningful connection: when the member finds a good connection they send a message, inside of LinkedIn, they include the friend and create a message such as:
"Hi Nate,

I would like to introduce you to my friend Max. He's on my softball team and he is a seasoned product manager who is interested in your advice and expertise around medical device manufacturing as he is seeking to transition from Company X. I am including him on this message and will invite him to reach out to you.

Please let me know what I can be on the look-out for you. I know that when good people meet good things happen.

Be well, my thoughtful friend,
Anne

Nate Nelson: nate.nelson@me.com
Max Smith: maxsmith2@gmail.com"

TIP: I always include the email addresses for each person in the introduction email.

Do you know what your online brand says about you?
Executives and Sales people with an understanding of their own digital visibility are more likely to add credibility and value to their organizations. Are you digitally dressed for success? member_projects_collection.name: Meaningful Connections LinkedIn Networking Parties
member_projects_collection.description:
Here's how a Meaningful Connections LinkedIn Party works:
Invite: 3 to 5 people who have different but complimentary networks to a 'LinkedIn Party'.
Meet up: at a location with internet access for instance a coffee shop community room, local community center, library room, virtual office location, the outplacement companies meeting room. In Minneapolis / St. some of our grocery stores have free community rooms .
Bring: computers
Check settings: everyone has their connections open (check the Settings to open connections to Everyone).
Prepare: a list of 10 people that they'd like to meet: titles, industries, companies, specialties, location, size of company, (their target audience).
Take turns: each person gets 10 minutes to ask the other members to search for his / her targeted people.
Search: friends all go to the "Advanced" area located next to the white Search box at the top of the profile page and type in the targeted keywords, titles, industries, companies, locations, etc. and click search.
Make meaningful connection: when the member finds a good connection they send a message, inside of LinkedIn, they include the friend and create a message such as:
"Hi Nate,
I would like to introduce you to my friend Max. He's on my softball team and he is a seasoned product manager who is interested in your advice and expertise around medical device manufacturing as he is seeking to transition from Company X. I am including him on this message and will invite him to reach out to you.
Please let me know what I can be on the look-out for you. I know that when good people meet good things happen.
Be well, my thoughtful friend,
Anne
Nate Nelson: nate.nelson@me.com
Max Smith: maxsmith2@gmail.com"
TIP: I always include the email addresses for each person in the introduction email.

member_projects_collection.name: Meaningful Connections LinkedIn Networking Parties
member_projects_collection.description:
Here's how a Meaningful Connections LinkedIn Party works:

Invite: 3 to 5 people who have different but complimentary networks to a 'LinkedIn Party'.
Meet up: at a location with internet access for instance a coffee shop community room, local community center, library room, virtual office location, the outplacement companies meeting room. In Minneapolis / St. some of our grocery stores have free community rooms .
Bring: computers
Check settings: everyone has their connections open (check the Settings to open connections to Everyone).
Prepare: a list of 10 people that they'd like to meet: titles, industries, companies, specialties, location, size of company, (their target audience).
Take turns: each person gets 10 minutes to ask the other members to search for his / her targeted people.
Search: friends all go to the "Advanced" area located next to the white Search box at the top of the profile page and type in the targeted keywords, titles, industries, companies, locations, etc. and click search.
Make meaningful connection: when the member finds a good connection they send a message, inside of LinkedIn, they include the friend and create a message such as:
"Hi Nate,

I would like to introduce you to my friend Max. He's on my softball team and he is a seasoned product manager who is interested in your advice and expertise around medical device manufacturing as he is seeking to transition from Company X. I am including him on this message and will invite him to reach out to you.

Please let me know what I can be on the look-out for you. I know that when good people meet good things happen.

Be well, my thoughtful friend,
Anne

Nate Nelson: nate.nelson@me.com
Max Smith: maxsmith2@gmail.com"

TIP: I always include the email addresses for each person in the introduction email.

member_projects_collection.name: Meaningful Connections LinkedIn Networking Parties
member_projects_collection.description:
Here's how a Meaningful Connections LinkedIn Party works:

Invite: 3 to 5 people who have different but complimentary networks to a 'LinkedIn Party'.
Meet up: at a location with internet access for instance a coffee shop community room, local community center, library room, virtual office location, the outplacement companies meeting room. In Minneapolis / St. some of our grocery stores have free community rooms .
Bring: computers
Check settings: everyone has their connections open (check the Settings to open connections to Everyone).
Prepare: a list of 10 people that they'd like to meet: titles, industries, companies, specialties, location, size of company, (their target audience).
Take turns: each person gets 10 minutes to ask the other members to search for his / her targeted people.
Search: friends all go to the "Advanced" area located next to the white Search box at the top of the profile page and type in the targeted keywords, titles, industries, companies, locations, etc. and click search.
Make meaningful connection: when the member finds a good connection they send a message, inside of LinkedIn, they include the friend and create a message such as:
"Hi Nate,

I would like to introduce you to my friend Max. He's on my softball team and he is a seasoned product manager who is interested in your advice and expertise around medical device manufacturing as he is seeking to transition from Company X. I am including him on this message and will invite him to reach out to you.

Please let me know what I can be on the look-out for you. I know that when good people meet good things happen.

Be well, my thoughtful friend,
Anne

Nate Nelson: nate.nelson@me.com
Max Smith: maxsmith2@gmail.com"

TIP: I always include the email addresses for each person in the introduction email.

member_publications_collection.title: FORBES: Five Most Important Tips on LinkedIn by William Arruda Featuring Anne Pryor Client Headlines
member_publications_collection.description: 1. Headline. Your headline has the same function as the headline of an advertisement; its primary purpose is to get the target audience to want to read on. Yet most LinkedIn members think “headline = job title.” If you don’t write a headline, LinkedIn uses your current job title as a default, and that’s a real snooze. To have your headline work for you, it should say what you do and entice people to learn more about your services. Don’t make it all about you; make it about the people you serve. Tell viewers what you can do for them. The second crucial function of the headline is to serve as an online “magnet.” If you want to be found in a search, you have to pack your headline with the keywords for which you want to be known. Making this an even greater challenge, you need to accomplish all that in just 120 characters. Here are some excellent examples of headlines from LinkedIn trainer and coach Anne Pryor.

member_publications_collection.title: 10 LinkedIn Tips for Professional Services Business Development
member_publications_collection.description:
10 LinkedIn Profile Tips for Business Development
Over 70% of professionals services executives report that they use LinkedIn as their primary networking online tool.
1) Get your profile to 100% - this ensures that your profile will come up higher in searches.
2) Know your industry key words – create a list of key words that your clients use to find you when seeking to hire your services. Add these in the Specialties, Skills and Interests sections.
3) Build a Company page – create a free company page on LinkedIn. Go to Company, Add Page. Add key words in Specialties.
4) Get Recommendations – this is especially important for business development. (90% of my business comes from LinkedIn referrals.) Get them on your Profile and Company pages.
5) Use the Applications – upload your company PPT presentation with Slideshare. It's located under the MORE tab.
6) Start using Advanced Search.
7) Leverage the Companies tab to find prospects – do you have a list of target companies. See People, Departures, New Hires, Skills, revenues, growth, and news.
8) Invite the right Connections – connect with influencers and relevant contacts that you can help and that can help you.
9) Join Groups – the action in happening in Groups. Type in the Group categories that you’re interested in, like CPA referrals or Franchisees. Join the Groups; watch the Discussions, then start a Discussion. This is where the business development is really happening.
10) Start your marketing – using the Status Bar, ‘what are you working on’, sharing relevant tips that your connections would be interested in. My three strategies are: 1) Humble self-promotions, 2) Promotion of others and 3) information or education content. This information can be connected with your Twitter account, so keep the character count to 140 characters or less, about 15 words.

member_publications_collection.description: The Planner - Welcome to Bloomington, Minnesota, the hospitality hub of travelers around the world. We are dedicating this issue of The Planner to a new sort of traveler—the Millennial Traveler—who is no doubt changing the way you and countless other meeting and event planners operate every day. With all things digital changing your delegates’ preferences and expectations by the near nano-second, we have compiled an overview of this relatively new breed of traveler, researching their go-to websites and apps that they commonly use now and will undoubtedly use in the future, both in their personal and professional lives. Like you, we believe it is critical to understand these trends, fleeting or lasting as they may be, to provide the best experience possible for visitors to our city today and in the future. We also believe that technology is no panacea or substitute for exceptional customer service—something you can always expect from us, here at the Bloomington Convention and Visitors Bureau.

member_publications_collection.description: 1. Headline. Your headline has the same function as the headline of an advertisement; its primary purpose is to get the target audience to want to read on. Yet most LinkedIn members think “headline = job title.” If you don’t write a headline, LinkedIn uses your current job title as a default, and that’s a real snooze. To have your headline work for you, it should say what you do and entice people to learn more about your services. Don’t make it all about you; make it about the people you serve. Tell viewers what you can do for them. The second crucial function of the headline is to serve as an online “magnet.” If you want to be found in a search, you have to pack your headline with the keywords for which you want to be known. Making this an even greater challenge, you need to accomplish all that in just 120 characters. Here are some excellent examples of headlines from LinkedIn trainer and coach Anne Pryor.

member_publications_collection.title: 10 LinkedIn Tips for Professional Services Business Development
member_publications_collection.description:
10 LinkedIn Profile Tips for Business Development
Over 70% of professionals services executives report that they use LinkedIn as their primary networking online tool.
1) Get your profile to 100% - this ensures that your profile will come up higher in searches.
2) Know your industry key words – create a list of key words that your clients use to find you when seeking to hire your services. Add these in the Specialties, Skills and Interests sections.
3) Build a Company page – create a free company page on LinkedIn. Go to Company, Add Page. Add key words in Specialties.
4) Get Recommendations – this is especially important for business development. (90% of my business comes from LinkedIn referrals.) Get them on your Profile and Company pages.
5) Use the Applications – upload your company PPT presentation with Slideshare. It's located under the MORE tab.
6) Start using Advanced Search.
7) Leverage the Companies tab to find prospects – do you have a list of target companies. See People, Departures, New Hires, Skills, revenues, growth, and news.
8) Invite the right Connections – connect with influencers and relevant contacts that you can help and that can help you.
9) Join Groups – the action in happening in Groups. Type in the Group categories that you’re interested in, like CPA referrals or Franchisees. Join the Groups; watch the Discussions, then start a Discussion. This is where the business development is really happening.
10) Start your marketing – using the Status Bar, ‘what are you working on’, sharing relevant tips that your connections would be interested in. My three strategies are: 1) Humble self-promotions, 2) Promotion of others and 3) information or education content. This information can be connected with your Twitter account, so keep the character count to 140 characters or less, about 15 words.

I live my Freedom Portfolio Career Life. Yes, it is a real term for people who have many jobs, interests, and revenue streams. I have been living my dream life for 8 years and I had been planning this life, which I called my "Freedom Plan”, since I was 40 years old (I am now 55).

WHAT IS A PORTFOLIO CAREER?

A Portfolio Career includes a life that is tailored to an individual’s personality, goals, time, interests, and income needs. A Portfolio Career is a life in which instead of working a traditional full-time job, you work multiple part-time jobs (including part-time employment, temporary jobs, freelancing, and self-employment) with different employers, jobs that when combined are the equivalent of a full-time position. It could include:

member_publications_collection.title: 10 LinkedIn Tips for Professional Services Business Development
member_publications_collection.description:
10 LinkedIn Profile Tips for Business Development
Over 70% of professionals services executives report that they use LinkedIn as their primary networking online tool.
1) Get your profile to 100% - this ensures that your profile will come up higher in searches.
2) Know your industry key words – create a list of key words that your clients use to find you when seeking to hire your services. Add these in the Specialties, Skills and Interests sections.
3) Build a Company page – create a free company page on LinkedIn. Go to Company, Add Page. Add key words in Specialties.
4) Get Recommendations – this is especially important for business development. (90% of my business comes from LinkedIn referrals.) Get them on your Profile and Company pages.
5) Use the Applications – upload your company PPT presentation with Slideshare. It's located under the MORE tab.
6) Start using Advanced Search.
7) Leverage the Companies tab to find prospects – do you have a list of target companies. See People, Departures, New Hires, Skills, revenues, growth, and news.
8) Invite the right Connections – connect with influencers and relevant contacts that you can help and that can help you.
9) Join Groups – the action in happening in Groups. Type in the Group categories that you’re interested in, like CPA referrals or Franchisees. Join the Groups; watch the Discussions, then start a Discussion. This is where the business development is really happening.
10) Start your marketing – using the Status Bar, ‘what are you working on’, sharing relevant tips that your connections would be interested in. My three strategies are: 1) Humble self-promotions, 2) Promotion of others and 3) information or education content. This information can be connected with your Twitter account, so keep the character count to 140 characters or less, about 15 words.

member_publications_collection.title: BEST SELLING BOOK | "When Paradise Speaks" - A Remarkable, True Story of Friendship, After-Death Communication, and Art that Heals
member_publications_collection.description:
**FULL COLOR EDITION FEATURING LOVITUDE SOUL PAINTINGS**

An Inspiring, Powerful True Story of Messages from the Afterlife
﻿When Irene, one of three close friends, dies unexpectedly, the trio's lives intertwine in life-changing ways. Immediately following Irene's death, Risë begins to sense her friend's presence around her. While delivering her eulogy from the pulpit at Irene's Celebration of Life, Risë sees Irene sitting in the congregation, her long auburn hair reflecting light from the windows above. Irene is calm and joyful as she glances, smiling, over her family and friends.

A fascinating year unfolds as Risë receives continuous communication from Irene from the afterlife through lucid dreams, channeled messages, and synchronicities too profound to be manifestations of her imagination. Under the weekly guidance of a spiritual leadership coach, Risë commits to a disciplined practice of daily meditation, guided imagery, spiritual experiences, and journaling to document all that she is experiencing and to make sense of this new relationship with the afterlife.

One year later, Irene directs Risë to write this book from the journals she has filled, telling her that she will be her ghost writer from the other side. The book is to be shared with the world, offering hope and understanding that our loved ones are always with us from beyond the veil to bring comfort and support.

Weeks later, the third friend, Anne, receives instructions from Irene to begin creating large, inspiring, "peacock-colored" paintings, using special inks and her breath. Though Anne was not an artist and nor was Irene, the directions are specific that she is to breathe the souls of those who have passed into her paintings using this unusual technique. Within months, Anne has created hundreds of paintings. These astonishing showpieces, some of which are included in the book, are awakening others around the world to connect with the spirit world themselves.

member_publications_collection.description:
"Less than 50% of the workforce in the industrialized world will be in “proper” full-time jobs in organizations by the beginning of the 21st century.”

(Source: Charles Handy, author, professor, business executive, speaker – first to coin the term Portfolio Career in 1950)

I live my Freedom Portfolio Career Life. Yes, it is a real term for people who have many jobs, interests, and revenue streams. I have been living my dream life for 8 years and I had been planning this life, which I called my "Freedom Plan”, since I was 40 years old (I am now 55).

WHAT IS A PORTFOLIO CAREER?

A Portfolio Career includes a life that is tailored to an individual’s personality, goals, time, interests, and income needs. A Portfolio Career is a life in which instead of working a traditional full-time job, you work multiple part-time jobs (including part-time employment, temporary jobs, freelancing, and self-employment) with different employers, jobs that when combined are the equivalent of a full-time position. I live my Freedom Portfolio Career Life. Yes, it is a real term for people who have many jobs, interests, and revenue streams. I have been living my dream life for 8 years and I had been planning this life, which I called my "Freedom Plan”, since I was 40 years old (I am now 55).

WHAT IS A PORTFOLIO CAREER?

A Portfolio Career includes a life that is tailored to an individual’s personality, goals, time, interests, and income needs. A Portfolio Career is a life in which instead of working a traditional full-time job, you work multiple part-time jobs (including part-time employment, temporary jobs, freelancing, and self-employment) with different employers, jobs that when combined are the equivalent of a full-time position. It could include:

member_publications_collection.description: 1. Headline. Your headline has the same function as the headline of an advertisement; its primary purpose is to get the target audience to want to read on. Yet most LinkedIn members think “headline = job title.” If you don’t write a headline, LinkedIn uses your current job title as a default, and that’s a real snooze.  To have your headline work for you, it should say what you do and entice people to learn more about your services. Don’t make it all about you; make it about the people you serve. Tell viewers what you can do for them. The second crucial function of the headline is to serve as an online “magnet.” If you want to be found in a search, you have to pack your headline with the keywords for which you want to be known. Making this an even greater challenge, you need to accomplish all that in just 120 characters. Here are some excellent examples of headlines from LinkedIn trainer and coach Anne Pryor.

member_publications_collection.title: 10 LinkedIn Tips for Professional Services Business Development
member_publications_collection.description:
10 LinkedIn Profile Tips for Business Development
Over 70% of professionals services executives report that they use LinkedIn as their primary networking online tool.
1)	Get your profile to 100% - this ensures that your profile will come up higher in searches.
2)	Know your industry key words – create a list of key words that your clients use to find you when seeking to hire your services.  Add these  in the Specialties, Skills and Interests sections.
3)	Build a Company page – create a free company page on LinkedIn.  Go to Company, Add Page.  Add key words in Specialties.
4)	Get Recommendations – this is especially important for business development. (90% of my business comes from LinkedIn referrals.) Get them on your Profile and Company pages.
5)	Use the Applications – upload your company PPT presentation with Slideshare.  It's located under the MORE tab.
6)	Start using Advanced Search.
7)	Leverage the Companies tab to find prospects – do you have a list of target companies. See People, Departures, New Hires, Skills, revenues, growth, and news.
8)	Invite the right Connections – connect with influencers and relevant contacts that you can help and that can help you.
9)	Join Groups – the action in happening in Groups.  Type in the Group categories that you’re interested in, like CPA referrals or Franchisees.  Join the Groups; watch the Discussions, then start a Discussion.  This is where the business development is really happening.
10)	Start your marketing – using the Status Bar, ‘what are you working on’, sharing relevant tips that your connections would be interested in.  My three strategies are: 1) Humble self-promotions, 2) Promotion of others and 3) information or education content.  This information can be connected with your Twitter account, so keep the character count to 140 characters or less, about 15 words.

In front of clients, she was always prepared, thoughtful, relevant and articulate at demonstrating her expertise on industry issues or solving problems. In front of colleagues, she always brought positive energy and enthusiasm to projects. Her ability to develop and nurture relationships is a unique gift and always in high demand.”

“Anne is a gem.  She says what she means, she cares deeply about people and their long term wellness and success and it shows in her work.  She is able to think of how to make connections for people in a way that brings out the best results and qualities in everyone. I look forward to working with her going forward on many things and recommend her to anyone that needs to learn new skills, tap into their greatest gifts or make the most of genuine connections.  She's a A+ person.”

“My recommendation to anyone reading this is to get to know Anne Pryor. 
She is a creative human being who effortlessly organizes business scenarios and connects people for their highest good.
I worked with her initially in the 1990's, putting together videos for her when she coordinated marketing for Camp Snoopy and the Mall of America. It was a high profile project, and typically, I would have expected it to be a big challenge. Between her organizational skills and calm understanding of the project, it was both fun and successful.
I highly recommend Anne.”

“Anne Pryor is an amazing human being! My job was recently eliminated at Allina Hospitals & Clinics so I was given the benefit of working with Career Partners International to help me with my job transition. Little did I know I would meet such an awesome, inspiring professional like Anne Pryor, my career coach. Quite frankly, she has blown me out of the water with her unwavering professionalism, attitude and commitment to help me find my next job opportunity. She's an incredibly kind and compassionate person and her listening skills are stellar. She gives 100% and then some to her clients. In just one week working with Anne, my networking skills have profoundly improved along with my resume, interviewing skills and a host of other tools that CPI gives you. In just one week of unemployment, I already have several interviews set up because of Anne and the great people at CPI. Anne has given me the competitive edge and confidence to land an even better job offer!”

“Anne brings a rare combination of gifts to everything she touches. She balances high level insights with practical actions that produce results. She quickly sees through situations and identifies courses of action that accelerate progress. And more importantly, she helps others to do the same. She cares deeply and genuinely about helping people and is able connect others to their natural passions, so they can contribute more successfully and enjoy life more fully. This is what makes her such an incredible leader and coach.

She is also highly innovative, while being extremely grounded. I hope you have a chance to meet Anne and experience her exceptional qualities of compassion, strength, honesty and integrity in action. She is inspiring.”

“Anne Pryor is an incredible inventor of masterful connections. She sees opportunities and solutions that match the gifts and talents of individuals and organizations with a primary need in the marketplace. Her ability to envision the possibilities and to offer tangible suggestions about next steps is extraordinary. Anne brings out the best in people with her compassion, enthusiasm, vision and gratitude. You will be amazed at the outcomes that manifest from her leadership. I highly recommend Anne Pryor!”

“Anne has a wonderful rapport with people and an ability to connect with every client that she is working with. She has excellent written and verbal communication skills and is extremely organized.

She accomplishes tasks with great initiative and always has a positive attitude and approach to problem solving. I respect her love for life and her unique ability to share her knowledge and insights with everyone she touches.”

“Anne is an exceptional connector, business partner, program and solution development creator. She sees the larger view and easily selects and motivates a team to develop solutions that make a difference. Anne is also a joy to work with”
“Anne is an exceptional program and solution development strategist and manager. She sees the larger view and can select and motivate a team to create new solutions. Anne is also a joy to work with.”

“Anne Pryor is one of the new gifts in my life. She came highly recommended to me as ‘someone I ought to know’ whose values and philosophies were aligned with my own. What a delight to know her! Anne has a deep passion for people and a genuine desire to see them succeed. She listens with her whole being and yearns to support those in her network in their journey toward success. My life is richer because of knowing Anne! She radiates life, gentleness, and compassion. I wear her Lovitude necklace with pride, as my reminder to focus on the all-important: Love and Gratitude. Thank you, Anne!”

“Anne has a great passion for her work and her combination of creativity and business sense makes for a wonderful partner. She genuinely cares for the people she works with and is committed to self-improvement and helping others reach their goals and potential.  I highly recommend Anne Pryor.”

“Anne Pryor's breadth and depth of professional Twin Cities contacts is legendary. She makes introductions generously and perceptively; and her reputation is impeccable and well-respected. When I relocated to the Twin Cities in the midst of a career transition, Anne's introductions literally opened doors to significant professional opportunities and social connections. A year after crossing paths with Anne, I have a flourishing new career with major clients and valued friendships that developed directly out of the introductions Anne made on my behalf. Anyone who is interested in expanding circles of influence should know Anne Pryor.”

“Anne is everything. Inspirational. Connected. Personal. Understanding. Connected. Intelligent. Strategic. Connected. Progressive. Thoughtful. Kind. Elegant. Connected. Innovative. Creative. Anne has been instrumental in our business and has impacted many other people in her good deeds and intelligence. If you want to know good people, Anne is the first person to introduce yourself to at a party. And, there is a reason why "connected" appears more than once in the list of words. Anne is.”

“Anne is, as trite as it might sound, amazing. We worked together on several projects for multiple clients, both internal and external. She is one of the smartest people I know. She's also one of the most compassionate, caring and spritually connected people I've known. She brings a zen-like perspective to a promotional assignment, a sophisticated eye to the seemingly mundane -- and what a creative mind!”
“Within two days of hiring Anne Pryor to build my inking branding and LinkedIn my phone was ringing off the hook. I had four solid job offers within a week. I highly recommend her.”

“For anyone looking to differentiate themselves on LinkedIn, you need to look no further than Anne Pryor.  Her generous heart, cut-to-the-chase style and passion for helping others truly makes her contribution remarkable.  I  highly recommend Anne...you cannot afford to NOT use Anne's wisdom to re-position yourself (and your career) on LinkedIn.”

“I highly recommend Anne Pryor as a rock star coach and expert advisor who can guide you in reimagining your LinkedIn profile. Anne's LinkedIn courses are action-packed with useful information and best practices that empower you to improve your branding and profile. I learned about how to build a 'portfolio career' from Anne and have enjoyed success in starting my own consulting business and being appointed to a company board.
